---
import ArticleCard from "../../../components/ArticleCard";
import BaseLayout from "../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import { englishSite } from "../../../lib/site";

const title = "Prompt, Skill, and Agent: A Practical Difference for Workflows";
const description =
  "A plain-English framework for separating one-off instructions, reusable procedures, and AI workers with tools.";
---

<BaseLayout
  title={title}
  description={description}
  type="article"
  lang="en"
  siteName={englishSite.name}
  siteTitle={englishSite.title}
  locale={englishSite.locale}
>
  <article class="container article-shell">
    <header class="article-header">
      <p class="article-back-link">
        <a class="text-link" href="/en/articles/">Back to English articles</a>
      </p>
      <div class="article-card-meta">
        <span>Framework</span>
        <time datetime="2026-05-27">May 27, 2026</time>
        <span>8 min read</span>
      </div>
      <h1>{title}</h1>
      <p class="hero-lede">{description}</p>
      <div class="tag-row">
        <span>Prompt</span>
        <span>Skill</span>
        <span>Agent</span>
      </div>
    </header>

    <div class="prose">
      <p>
        Teams often use the words prompt, workflow, automation, and agent as if they all mean the same thing.
        That makes AI adoption harder. A one-off instruction, a reusable procedure, and an AI worker with tools
        need different levels of clarity and control.
      </p>

      <p>
        The practical distinction is simple: a prompt tells AI what to do now, a skill explains how to do a
        recurring task, and an agent acts through tools while making limited decisions inside a boundary.
      </p>

      <h2>Prompt: the instruction for this run</h2>
      <p>
        A prompt is the message that starts a task. It may include context, constraints, style rules, examples,
        and output format. A good prompt reduces ambiguity and helps AI produce something useful on the first run.
      </p>

      <p>
        Prompts are best for flexible work: brainstorming, drafting, rewriting, comparing options, summarizing
        material, or asking AI to plan a task before execution. The limitation is that a prompt is easy to lose.
        If the same prompt is useful twice, it should probably be documented.
      </p>

      <h2>Skill: the reusable procedure</h2>
      <p>
        A skill is a saved way of doing work. It contains the task purpose, required inputs, process steps,
        output format, checks, examples, and warnings. The point is not to make the instruction longer. The point
        is to make the work repeatable.
      </p>

      <p>
        For example, "write an article outline" is a prompt. "Create an article outline for this site using the
        editorial policy, internal links, audience definition, and final checklist" is closer to a skill. It can
        be run again because the procedure is visible.
      </p>

      <h2>Agent: a bounded AI worker with tools</h2>
      <p>
        An agent is useful when the task requires multiple steps, file access, code edits, commands, browsing, or
        decisions based on intermediate results. A coding agent such as Codex is a good example: it can inspect a
        repository, edit files, run a build, review the diff, commit, and push when allowed.
      </p>

      <p>
        The word "agent" should also raise the standard for guardrails. The more an AI can do, the clearer its
        permissions must be. Define the workspace, forbidden actions, approval points, verification commands, and
        completion criteria before giving it broad work.
      </p>

      <h2>Where MCP, tools, hooks, and human approval fit</h2>
      <p>
        Tools are the external capabilities an AI can use: file editing, shell commands, browsers, databases, or
        design systems. MCP is one way to expose those capabilities in a structured way. Hooks can run checks or
        trigger repeatable steps around the agent workflow.
      </p>

      <p>
        Human approval is the control point. It belongs near production changes, account operations, payments,
        DNS, customer data, legal commitments, and any action where a wrong step has a real cost. A mature AI
        workflow makes these approval points explicit instead of relying on memory.
      </p>

      <h2>A practical decision rule</h2>
      <p>
        Use this rule when deciding what to build:
      </p>

      <ul>
        <li>If the task is new or exploratory, start with a prompt.</li>
        <li>If the task repeats, turn the prompt into a skill.</li>
        <li>If the skill needs tools, files, or step-by-step execution, consider an agent.</li>
        <li>If the agent can affect production or external systems, add human approval.</li>
        <li>If the output will be reused, add evaluation criteria before saving it.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>How this connects to AI operations</h2>
      <p>
        AI operations is the habit of turning useful AI work into a system. The system does not have to be heavy.
        A folder of prompts, a set of skills, a build checklist, a launch log, and a few guardrails can already
        change how reliably a small team works.
      </p>

      <p>
        The core article <a href="/en/articles/stop-asking-start-building-ai-operations/">Stop Asking AI. Start
        Building AI-Powered Operations.</a> explains the broader loop: ask, build, save, and improve.
      </p>

      <h2>Next read</h2>
      <p>
        Return to <a href="/en/articles/stop-asking-start-building-ai-operations/">the operating model article</a>
        if you want the larger workflow view, or open the <a href="/en/articles/">English article index</a> to keep
        the English mini-site path focused.
      </p>
    </div>

    <section class="article-footer-nav">
      <h2>Next read</h2>
      <div class="article-grid">
        <ArticleCard
          client:visible
          title="Stop Asking AI. Start Building AI-Powered Operations."
          description="A practical introduction to turning AI conversations into reusable workflows, guardrails, and working assets."
          href="/en/articles/stop-asking-start-building-ai-operations/"
          category="Operating model"
          date="May 27, 2026"
          readTime="7 min read"
          tags={["AI operations", "Workflow", "Guardrails"]}
        />
      </div>
    </section>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
